body:
Verilator fails to automatically upcast a derived class object to its base class when passed as a ref parameter to a function, even though this is valid SystemVerilog according to IEEE 1800-2017. The error indicates that automatic upcasting is not supported for ref arguments.

```
%Error: tb.sv:41:26: Ref argument requires matching types; port 'tr' requires 'class{}BaseTransaction' but connection is 'class{}MyTransaction'.
                   : ... note: In instance 'tb_top'
-node: VARREF 0x5555565bc900 <e3215#> {e41ba} @dt=0x5555565bc4b0@(w0)class:MyTransaction  tx pkg=0x5555565b0640 [RV] <- VAR 0x5555565b2190 <e3207#> {e36ax} @dt=0x5555565bc4b0@(w0)class:MyTransaction  tx [FUNC] [VAUTOM]  MEMBER
   41 |         callback.process(tx);   
      |                          ^~
        ... See the manual at https://verilator.org/verilator_doc.html?v=5.039 for more assistance.
```

**Environment**

Verilator Version: latest main
Platform: Linux

**Minimal Reproducible Example**
```
// Base class
class BaseTransaction;
    int data;
    function new(int data = 0);
        this.data = data;
    endfunction
endclass

// Derived class
class MyTransaction extends BaseTransaction;
    int extra_field;
    function new(int data = 0, int extra = 0);
        super.new(data);
        this.extra_field = extra;
    endfunction
endclass

// Callback class that expects base class reference
class MyCallback;
    // This function expects a ref to BaseTransaction
    function void process(ref BaseTransaction tr);
        tr.data = tr.data + 1;  // Modify the base class field
        $display("Processed transaction, data = %0d", tr.data);
    endfunction
endclass

// Test class that demonstrates the issue
class TestClass;
    MyCallback callback;

    function new();
        callback = new();
    endfunction

    task run();
        MyTransaction tx = new(42, 100);  // Create derived class object

        $display("Before: data = %0d", tx.data);

        // ERROR: This should work - derived class should upcast to base class
        callback.process(tx);  // This line causes the error

        $display("After: data = %0d", tx.data);
    endtask
endclass

// Top-level testbench
module tb_top;
    TestClass test;

    initial begin
        test = new();
        test.run();
        $finish;
    end
endmodule

```

**Steps to Reproduce**

Save the code above to a file called tb.sv
Run: `verilator --binary --timing tb.sv`
Observe the upcasting error

**Expected Behavior**
According to IEEE 1800-2017, a derived class object should be automatically upcast to its base class when passed to a function expecting the base class type. The code should compile and run successfully, with the MyTransaction object being treated as a BaseTransaction inside the process function. I checked on Vivado, where this seems to work.


**Further Notes**
Manual cast operator also fails
```
task run();
    MyTransaction tx = new(42, 100);
    // This also fails in Verilator:
    callback.process(BaseTransaction'(tx));  // Still produces an
endtask
```

